# Artifact Description
The artifact I selected for the software design and engineering category is my Android mobile inventory application, 
originally developed in CS 360. The application allows users to create an account, sign in, manage inventory items, 
and store item data locally through SQLite. It also includes a settings screen that supports SMS notification 
permissions and user preferences. I originally created this project during CS 360 as part of my work in mobile 
application development.

# Why I Selected This Artifact
I included this artifact in my ePortfolio because it best reflects my growth in software engineering and application design. 
The project demonstrates more than the ability to create a working application. It shows that I can evaluate an 
existing codebase, identify structural weaknesses, and apply improvements that make the software easier to maintain and extend. 
This application combines user authentication, inventory management, local database storage, and configurable settings 
within one cohesive mobile solution.

This artifact also showcases several software engineering strengths. The application demonstrates modular design by 
separating responsibilities across multiple classes. LoginActivity handles registration and authentication, 
InventoryActivity manages the inventory interface and item updates, SmsActivity manages SMS-related settings, 
AppDatabaseHelper handles database creation and CRUD operations, InventoryAdapter manages RecyclerView display behavior, 
and SessionManager maintains the active user session. This separation of concerns shows my understanding of how 
well-structured software is built through focused, reusable components rather than a single oversized class.

The enhancement improved the artifact by making the codebase easier to follow, test, and maintain. Instead of 
concentrating multiple responsibilities in a small number of files, the revised version uses clearer separation 
between database logic, session management, interface behavior, and list display. These changes improved readability 
and aligned the project more closely with software engineering best practices such as modularity, maintainability, 
and long-term usability. Through this enhancement, I demonstrated skills in mobile application design, object-oriented 
organization, software maintenance, and user-centered improvement.

# Reflection on the Enhancement Process
This enhancement reinforced that software engineering is not only about writing code that works. It is also about 
designing code that remains understandable, maintainable, and adaptable over time. While revising this artifact, 
I gained a stronger appreciation for separation of concerns and for the value of assigning clear responsibilities 
  to individual classes. One of the most important lessons I learned was that maintainability improves when database 
logic, session handling, display logic, and activity logic are not tightly mixed together.

The main challenge I faced was improving the structure of the application without changing its original purpose or 
disrupting existing functionality. I also had to ensure that the login flow, inventory management features, and SMS 
settings continued to work together consistently after the code was reorganized. Working through those challenges 
strengthened my understanding of how thoughtful design decisions improve both software quality and the developer experience.

I also incorporated feedback by making the narrative more specific about the design improvements I made and by more 
clearly connecting those improvements to software engineering principles such as modularity, separation of concerns, 
and maintainability. That revision made the explanation more professional and more clearly aligned with the purpose 
of the ePortfolio.

This artifact fully supports Outcome Three and Outcome Four because it demonstrates my ability to design and 
evaluate a computing solution and improve it using appropriate practices and tools. It also partially supports 
Outcome Two because I am able to explain the purpose of the artifact and communicate the value of the enhancement 
clearly. Outcome Five is only partially met in this artifact because, although the project includes validation and 
safer structure, the enhancement was not primarily focused on security.
